{"title_page": "Go Stupid", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 song by Polo G, Stunna 4 Vegas and NLE Choppa featuring Mike Will Made It}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Go Stupid\n| cover      = Polo G - Go Stupid.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Polo G]], [[Stunna 4 Vegas]] and [[NLE Choppa]] featuring [[Mike Will Made It]]\n| released   = February 14, 2020\n| genre      = <!-- Please source genres -->\n| length     = 2:46\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     =\n| producer   =\n* [[Mike Will Made It]]\n* [[Tay Keith]]\n| chronology = Polo G\n| prev_title = First Place\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Stunna 4 Vegas]]\n| type       = single\n| prev_title = Change My Life\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| title      = Go Stupid\n| year       = 2020\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[NLE Choppa]]\n| type       = single\n| prev_title = Exotic\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| title      = Go Stupid\n| year       = 2020\n| next_title = 100 Shots \n| next_year  = 2020\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Mike Will Made It]]\n| type       = single\n| prev_title = Valentine\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| title      = Go Stupid\n| year       = 2020\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Go Stupid'''\" is a song by American rappers [[Polo G]], [[Stunna 4 Vegas]], and [[NLE Choppa]] featuring producer [[Mike Will Made It]]. It was released as a single on February 14, 2020. The song has gone viral on video-sharing app [[TikTok]].<ref name=\"TikTok Songs\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/tiktok-songs-worth-listening-to/|title= 12 Songs Blowing Up on TikTok (That Are Actually Worth Listening to)|last=McKinney|first=Jessica|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe track debuted and peaked at number 60 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making it the second Hot 100 entry for Polo G and Stunna 4 Vegas, and the fourth for NLE Choppa.\n\n==Background==\nThe track was first announced in an [[Instagram]] post by Polo G on February 7, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B8RkeDlFucP/|title=Polo.G\ud83d\udc10 (@polo.capalot) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|via=Instagram|date=February 7, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> A snippet of the track was later posted on Polo's Instagram account on February 12, two days before the release of the track.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B8ewhIMldwh/|title=Polo.G\ud83d\udc10 (@polo.capalot) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|via=[[Instagram]]|date=February 12, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\nThe song has no chorus, instead finding all three rappers \"ripping up\" the [[Mike Will Made-It]]/[[Tay Keith]] beat.<ref name=\"Stereogum\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2073639/polo-g-go-stupid-feat-stunna-4-vegas-nle-choppa/video/|title=Polo G \u2013 \"Go Stupid\" (Feat. Stunna 4 Vegas & NLE Choppa)|work=[[Stereogum]]|last=Breihan|first=Tom|date=February 14, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nPolo G has received particular praise for his verse.<ref name=\"Stereogum\" /><ref name=\"COS\">{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/stream-polo-g-go-stupid-song-video/amp/|title=Polo G Unleashes New Single \"Go Stupid\": Stream|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Schatz|first=Lake|date=February 14, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Alex Zidel of ''[[HotNewHipHop]]'' said that Polo G \"continued to prove that he can rap his ass off\", and that he had \"fast-paced bars\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/polo-g-grabs-nle-choppa-and-stunna-4-vegas-for-go-stupid-new-song.1986176.html|title=Polo G Grabs NLE Choppa & Stunna 4 Vegas For \"Go Stupid\"|last=Zidel|first=Alex|date=February 14, 2020|website=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Jessica McKinney of [[Complex (magazine)|''Complex'']] called the song a \"rowdy club record\".<ref name=\"TikTok Songs\" />\n\n==Tik Tok tutorials==\nThe song has become popular on video-sharing app [[TikTok]] where fans use it to create viral [[tutorial|tutorials]] in a\u00a0virtual classroom. These videos draw inspiration from the song's official music video, which is set in a high school.<ref name=\"TikTok Songs\" />\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for the track was released on February 14, 2020. It features all three rappers partying and dancing at a high school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PEEoaKwwxbg|title=Polo G, Stunna 4 Vegas & NLE Choppa feat. Mike WiLL Made-It - Go Stupid (Official Video)|via=YouTube|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Chart (2020)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|28|artist=NLE Choppa|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland3|97|artist=Polo G|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| New Zealand Hot Singles ([[Recorded Music NZ|RMNZ]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/hotsingles?chart=4828|title=NZ Hot Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n| 16\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|60|artist=NLE Choppa|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrandbhiphop|29|artist=NLE Choppa|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/songs/2020-02-14/|title=Top 100 Songs|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n| 33\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:NLE Choppa songs]]\n[[Category:Polo G songs]]\n[[Category:TikTok songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 song by Polo G, Stunna 4 Vegas and NLE Choppa featuring Mike Will Made It}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Go Stupid\n| cover      = Polo G - Go Stupid.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Polo G]], [[Stunna 4 Vegas]] and [[NLE Choppa]] featuring [[Mike Will Made It]]\n| released   = February 14, 2020\n| genre      = <!-- Please source genres -->\n| length     = 2:46\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     =\n| producer   =\n* [[Mike Will Made It]]\n* [[Tay Keith]]\n| chronology = Polo G\n| prev_title = First Place\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Stunna 4 Vegas]]\n| type       = single\n| prev_title = Change My Life\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| title      = Go Stupid\n| year       = 2020\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[NLE Choppa]]\n| type       = single\n| prev_title = Exotic\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| title      = Go Stupid\n| year       = 2020\n| next_title = 100 Shots \n| next_year  = 2020\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Mike Will Made It]]\n| type       = single\n| prev_title = Valentine\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| title      = Go Stupid\n| year       = 2020\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Go Stupid'''\" is a song by American rappers [[Polo G]], [[Stunna 4 Vegas]], and [[NLE Choppa]] featuring producer [[Mike Will Made It]]. It was released as a single on February 14, 2020. The song has gone viral on video-sharing app [[TikTok]].<ref name=\"TikTok Songs\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/tiktok-songs-worth-listening-to/|title= 12 Songs Blowing Up on TikTok (That Are Actually Worth Listening to)|last=McKinney|first=Jessica|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe track debuted and peaked at number 60 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making it the second Hot 100 entry for Polo G and Stunna 4 Vegas, and the fourth for NLE Choppa.\n\n==Background==\nThe track was first announced in an [[Instagram]] post by Polo G on February 7, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B8RkeDlFucP/|title=Polo.G\ud83d\udc10 (@polo.capalot) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|via=Instagram|date=February 7, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> A snippet of the track was later posted on Polo's Instagram account on February 12, two days before the release of the track.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B8ewhIMldwh/|title=Polo.G\ud83d\udc10 (@polo.capalot) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|via=[[Instagram]]|date=February 12, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\nThe song has no chorus, instead finding all three rappers \"ripping up\" the [[Mike Will Made-It]]/[[Tay Keith]] beat.<ref name=\"Stereogum\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2073639/polo-g-go-stupid-feat-stunna-4-vegas-nle-choppa/video/|title=Polo G \u2013 \"Go Stupid\" (Feat. Stunna 4 Vegas & NLE Choppa)|work=[[Stereogum]]|last=Breihan|first=Tom|date=February 14, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nPolo G has recieved particular praise for his verse.<ref name=\"Stereogum\" /><ref name=\"COS\">{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/stream-polo-g-go-stupid-song-video/amp/|title=Polo G Unleashes New Single \"Go Stupid\": Stream|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Schatz|first=Lake|date=February 14, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Alex Zidel of ''[[HotNewHipHop]]'' said that Polo G \"continued to prove that he can rap his ass off\", and that he had \"fast-paced bars\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/polo-g-grabs-nle-choppa-and-stunna-4-vegas-for-go-stupid-new-song.1986176.html|title=Polo G Grabs NLE Choppa & Stunna 4 Vegas For \"Go Stupid\"|last=Zidel|first=Alex|date=February 14, 2020|website=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Jessica McKinney of [[Complex (magazine)|''Complex'']] called the song a \"rowdy club record\".<ref name=\"TikTok Songs\" />\n\n==Tik Tok tutorials==\nThe song has become popular on video-sharing app [[TikTok]] where fans use it to create viral [[tutorial|tutorials]] in a\u00a0virtual classroom. These videos draw inspiration from the song's official music video, which is set in a high school.<ref name=\"TikTok Songs\" />\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for the track was released on February 14, 2020. It features all three rappers partying and dancing at a high school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PEEoaKwwxbg|title=Polo G, Stunna 4 Vegas & NLE Choppa feat. Mike WiLL Made-It - Go Stupid (Official Video)|via=YouTube|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Chart (2020)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|28|artist=NLE Choppa|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland3|97|artist=Polo G|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| New Zealand Hot Singles ([[Recorded Music NZ|RMNZ]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/hotsingles?chart=4828|title=NZ Hot Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n| 16\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|60|artist=NLE Choppa|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrandbhiphop|29|artist=NLE Choppa|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/songs/2020-02-14/|title=Top 100 Songs|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n| 33\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:NLE Choppa songs]]\n[[Category:Polo G songs]]\n[[Category:TikTok songs]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "recieved > received", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Go_Stupid"}
{"title_page": "Huel", "text_new": "{{short description|Powdered food product and company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Huel Inc.\n| logo = Huel_Official_Logo.png\n| type = [[Privately held company]]\n| industry = [[Meal replacement]]s\n| products = Huel\n| founders = Julian Hearn, James Collier\n| location = UK: [[Tring]], [[Hertfordshire]]<BR>USA: [[Los Angeles]]<BR>Germany: [[Berlin]]\n| founded = {{start date and age|2014}}\n| website = {{URL|https://huel.com/}}\n}}\n[[File:Huel-product-image.jpg|thumb|Huel powdered food packaging]]\n'''Huel''', manufactured by Huel Inc., is a [[meal replacement]] available in powder, liquid, or bar forms.<ref>\n{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/food-and-drink/features/is-powdered-food-the-future-huel-put-to-the-test/ | title=Is powdered food the future? Huel put to the test | first=Abigail | last=Butcher | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=9 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/09/lunch-fatigue-meal-replacement-powder-huel | title=My week on powdered food made me feel less spaceman, more idiot | first=Peter | last=Robinson | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=9 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=McEachran | first=Rich | title=Is powdered food an eco-dream or just weird? | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/2015/dec/17/huel-ambronite-powdered-food-eco-dream-or-just-weird | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=17 December 2015}}</ref> Huel is made from [[oats]], [[rice protein]], [[pea protein]], [[sunflower]], [[flaxseed]], [[coconut oil]] [[Medium-chain triglyceride|MCT]]s, and several [[dietary supplement]]s (vitamins and minerals). It is sweetened with [[sucralose]], [[maltodextrin]], and [[xylitol]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2016/jul/31/huel-human-fuel-hi-tech-food-powder | title=Could you stomach Huel, the food of the future? | first=Carole | last=Cadwalladr | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=31 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe name Huel is a [[portmanteau]] of \"human fuel\".<ref name=live>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health-fitness/body/week-huel-can-really-live-nutritionally-complete-powder/ | title=My week on Huel: can you really live off nutritionally-complete powder? | last=Ough | first=Tom | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=15 February 2017 | issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nHuel has sold over 50 million meals in more than 80 countries.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://huel.com/pages/50-million-meals | title=50 million meals sold in 80+ countries | publisher=Huel}}</ref>\n\nApproximately 70% of the company's customers are male.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/vb9nb4/huel-soylent-effects-miss-food | title=I Swapped Food for Huel for a Week, to See If It Would Ruin My Life | first=Hayden | last=Vernon | work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] | date=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nHuel was founded by Julian Hearn in 2014 in [[Aylesbury]], England.<ref name=aboutus>{{Cite web | url=https://huel.com/pages/about-us | title=About Huel | publisher=Huel}}</ref> The original recipe was formulated by registered [[nutritionist]] James Collier, founder and former owner of MuscleTalk, a [[bodybuilding]] website,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.muscletalk.co.uk/about/ | publisher=MuscleTalk | title=About MuscleTalk}}</ref> with the intention of providing the [[Dietary Reference Intake|recommended daily amounts]] (RDAs) of nutrients as stipulated by the [[European Food Safety Authority]], in a [[vegan]] and environmentally friendly product.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://discuss.huel.com/t/how-sustainable-is-huel-really/5509/11 | title=How sustainable is Huel, really? | publisher=Huel}}</ref>\n\nThe first Huel product was shipped in June 2015. A version for [[gluten-free diet]]s was launched in 2016.<ref name=versions>{{Cite web | url=https://uk.huel.com/pages/versions-of-huel | title=Version History | publisher=Huel}}</ref> In 2016 Huel began shipping to the rest of Europe.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.myrecipes.com/extracrispy/european-soylent-competitor-huel-is-coming-to-america | title=European Soylent Competitor Huel Is Coming to America | last=Nickalls | first=Sammy | work=Myrecipes.com | date=13 June 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, it became available in the United States.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/huel-announces-commitment-to-the-us-market-with-new-product-launches-300756680.html | title=Huel Announces Commitment to the U.S. Market with New Product Launches | publisher=[[PR Newswire]] | date=November 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, former Life Health Foods UK chief executive James McMaster was appointed as [[chief executive officer]] of the company to oversee its international expansion.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.thegrocer.co.uk/movers/james-mcmaster-is-new-ceo-of-complete-food-brand-huel/560223.article | title=James McMaster is new CEO of \u2018complete food\u2019 brand Huel | last=Perkins | first=Carina | work=TheGrocer.co.uk | date=16 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nA typical serving of Huel Powder contains 400 calories.<ref name=nutritional>{{Cite web | url=https://uk.huel.com/pages/nutritional-information-and-ingredients | title=Nutritional Information and Ingredients | publisher=Huel}}</ref>\n\n* '''Huel Powder''' - The first Huel product to be released, it has gone through several iterations since 2015. Huel is sold in 1.7kg bags in bulk or as a subscription, with oats as the primary ingredient followed by rice, pea protein, and [[micronutrient]]s. Huel Powder is made up of 37% carbohydrates, 30% fat, 30% protein, and 3% fibre.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://huel.com/pages/the-huel-powder-formula-explained | title=The Huel Powder Formula Explained | publisher=Huel}}</ref> Huel Powder v3.0 is available in seven flavors: Vanilla, Unflavoured & Unsweetened, Original, Coffee, Berry, Mint-Chocolate, and Chocolate.<ref name=nutritional/>\n* '''Huel Ready-To-Drink''' - Launched in 2018, Huel RTD is sold in packs of 12 bottles, in bulk, or as a subscription. Each bottle contains 500ml of Huel and provides 400 calories. Huel RTD is available in Berry, Vanilla and Chocolate flavors (UK and United States).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://huel.com/pages/the-huel-ready-to-drink-formula-explained | title=The Huel Ready-to-drink Formula Explained | publisher=Huel}}</ref> \n* '''Flavour Boosts''' - Huel also sells Flavour Boosts. These have no nutritional value and are designed to complement Huel Powder mixes. Eleven flavours of Flavour Boosts are available from Huel.\n* '''Huel Bars''' - Launched in 2017, the snack bars are vegan and gluten-free.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://huel.com/products/huel-bar | title=Huel Bars | publisher=Huel}}</ref> Huel Bars are made up of 36% carbohydrates, 35% fat, 24% protein, and 5% fibre.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://huel.com/pages/the-huel-bar-formula-explained | title=The Huel Bars Formula Explained | publisher=Huel}}</ref>\n* '''Huel Granola''' - Introduced in 2018, Huel Granola is composed primarily of rolled oats.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://uk.huel.com/pages/the-huel-granola-formula | title=The Huel Granola Formula | publisher=Huel}}</ref>\n\n==Reviews and reception==\nIn March 2016, an article in Coach magazine described Huel\u2019s basic flavour as \u201cunderwhelming\u201d, though the reviewer did note that the taste can be improved substantially with Flavour Boosts and home recipes.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.coachmag.co.uk/nutrition/5161/is-huel-the-future-of-food | title=Is Huel the Future of Food? | first=NICK | last=HARRIS-FRY | work=Coach Magazine | date=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, after a week-long Huel-only diet, journalist Peter Robinson wrote, \"there are lumps in the mixture\" and stated, \"Huel doesn\u2019t just sound like the act of vomiting, it actually feels like doing it backwards\".<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/09/lunch-fatigue-meal-replacement-powder-huel | title=My week on powdered food made me feel less spaceman, more idiot | last=Robinson | first=Peter | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Jared Hill said after a week-long Huel-only diet \"I had finally freed myself from the shackles of food consumption, and let me tell you, it felt amazing.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://medium.com/@jamchiller/one-week-on-huel-one-small-step-for-man-one-giant-leap-for-my-bowels-a9026a48d94d | title=A Week on Huel: One Small Step for Man, One Giant Leap for My Bowels | first=Jared | last=Hill | work=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] | date=September 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, after a week-long trial, Tom Ough, a journalist for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described his Huel-only diet as \"struggling to get enough down me to hit anywhere near my 2000-calorie RDA,\" saying, \"I got bored of having the same thing all the time, but have lost well over three kilos despite finding it filling. I've also felt healthy throughout the experiment.\"<ref name=live/> He concluded that Huel was \"very good\", but better when used only occasionally.<ref name=live/>\n\nIn July 2017, Huel was referred to as \"Hipster Gruel\" by [[Dave Gorman]] on ''[[Dave Gorman: Modern Life is Goodish]]''.<ref>{{cite AV media | url=https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x5t4wo8 | title=Dave Gorman- Modern Life is Goodish S4 E6 | via=[[Dailymotion]] | date=July 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, ''[[Forbes]]'' listed Huel amongst the best \u201cgadgets to keep you fit and healthy\u201d.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/leebelltech/2018/03/26/the-best-health-tech-2017/ | title=Best Health Tech: Gadgets to Help Keep You Fit And Healthy | first=Lee | last=Bell | work=[[Forbes]] | date=6 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Liquid diet]]\n* [[Meal replacement]]\n* [[Protein shake]]\n* [[Therapeutic food]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://huel.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Dietary supplements]]\n[[Category:Nutritional supplement companies]]\n[[Category:Veganism]]\n[[Category:Vegetarian diets]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Powdered food product and company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Huel Inc.\n| logo = Huel_Official_Logo.png\n| type = [[Privately held company]]\n| industry = [[Meal replacement]]s\n| products = Huel\n| founders = Julian Hearn, James Collier\n| location = UK: [[Tring]], [[Hertfordshire]]<BR>USA: [[Los Angeles]]<BR>Germany: [[Berlin]]\n| founded = {{start date and age|2014}}\n| website = {{URL|https://huel.com/}}\n}}\n[[File:Huel-product-image.jpg|thumb|Huel powdered food packaging]]\n'''Huel''', manufactured by Huel Inc., is a [[meal replacement]] available in powder, liquid, or bar forms.<ref>\n{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/food-and-drink/features/is-powdered-food-the-future-huel-put-to-the-test/ | title=Is powdered food the future? Huel put to the test | first=Abigail | last=Butcher | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=9 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/09/lunch-fatigue-meal-replacement-powder-huel | title=My week on powdered food made me feel less spaceman, more idiot | first=Peter | last=Robinson | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=9 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=McEachran | first=Rich | title=Is powdered food an eco-dream or just weird? | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/2015/dec/17/huel-ambronite-powdered-food-eco-dream-or-just-weird | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=17 December 2015}}</ref> Huel is made from [[oats]], [[rice protein]], [[pea protein]], [[sunflower]], [[flaxseed]], [[coconut oil]] [[Medium-chain triglyceride|MCT]]s, and several [[dietary supplement]]s (vitamins and minerals). It is sweetened with [[sucralose]], [[maltodextrin]], and [[xylitol]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2016/jul/31/huel-human-fuel-hi-tech-food-powder | title=Could you stomach Huel, the food of the future? | first=Carole | last=Cadwalladr | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=31 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe name Huel is a [[portmanteau]] of \"human fuel\".<ref name=live>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health-fitness/body/week-huel-can-really-live-nutritionally-complete-powder/ | title=My week on Huel: can you really live off nutritionally-complete powder? | last=Ough | first=Tom | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=15 February 2017 | issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nHuel has sold over 50 million meals in more than 80 countries.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://huel.com/pages/50-million-meals | title=50 million meals sold in 80+ countries | publisher=Huel}}</ref>\n\nApproximately 70% of the company's customers are male.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/vb9nb4/huel-soylent-effects-miss-food | title=I Swapped Food for Huel for a Week, to See If It Would Ruin My Life | first=Hayden | last=Vernon | work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] | date=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nHuel was founded by Julian Hearn in 2014 in [[Aylesbury]], England.<ref name=aboutus>{{Cite web | url=https://huel.com/pages/about-us | title=About Huel | publisher=Huel}}</ref> The original recipe was formulated by registered [[nutritionist]] James Collier, founder and former owner MuscleTalk, a [[bodybuilding]] website,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.muscletalk.co.uk/about/ | publisher=MuscleTalk | title=About MuscleTalk}}</ref> with the intention of providing the [[Dietary Reference Intake|recommended daily amounts]] (RDAs) of nutrients as stipulated by the [[European Food Safety Authority]], in a [[veganism]] and environmentally friendly product.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://discuss.huel.com/t/how-sustainable-is-huel-really/5509/11 | title=How sustainable is Huel, really? | publisher=Huel}}</ref>\n\nThe first Huel product was shipped in June 2015. A version for [[gluten-free diet]]s was launched in 2016.<ref name=versions>{{Cite web | url=https://uk.huel.com/pages/versions-of-huel | title=Version History | publisher=Huel}}</ref> In 2016 Huel began shipping to the rest of Europe.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.myrecipes.com/extracrispy/european-soylent-competitor-huel-is-coming-to-america | title=European Soylent Competitor Huel Is Coming to America | last=Nickalls | first=Sammy | work=Myrecipes.com | date=13 June 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, it became available in the United States.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/huel-announces-commitment-to-the-us-market-with-new-product-launches-300756680.html | title=Huel Announces Commitment to the U.S. Market with New Product Launches | publisher=[[PR Newswire]] | date=November 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, former Life Health Foods UK chief executive James McMaster was appointed as [[chief executive officer]] of the company to oversee its international expansion.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.thegrocer.co.uk/movers/james-mcmaster-is-new-ceo-of-complete-food-brand-huel/560223.article | title=James McMaster is new CEO of \u2018complete food\u2019 brand Huel | last=Perkins | first=Carina | work=TheGrocer.co.uk | date=16 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nA typical serving of Huel Powder contains 400 calories.<ref name=nutritional>{{Cite web | url=https://uk.huel.com/pages/nutritional-information-and-ingredients | title=Nutritional Information and Ingredients | publisher=Huel}}</ref>\n\n* '''Huel Powder''' - The first Huel product to be released, it has gone through several iterations since 2015. Huel is sold in 1.7kg bags in bulk or as a subscription, with oats as the primary ingredient followed by rice, pea protein, and [[micronutrient]]s. Huel Powder is made up of 37% carbohydrates, 30% fat, 30% protein, and 3% fibre.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://huel.com/pages/the-huel-powder-formula-explained | title=The Huel Powder Formula Explained | publisher=Huel}}</ref> Huel Powder v3.0 is available in seven flavors: Vanilla, Unflavoured & Unsweetened, Original, Coffee, Berry, Mint-Chocolate, and Chocolate.<ref name=nutritional/>\n* '''Huel Ready-To-Drink''' - Launched in 2018, Huel RTD is sold in packs of 12 bottles, in bulk, or as a subscription. Each bottle contains 500ml of Huel and provides 400 calories. Huel RTD is available in Berry, Vanilla and Chocolate flavors (UK and United States).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://huel.com/pages/the-huel-ready-to-drink-formula-explained | title=The Huel Ready-to-drink Formula Explained | publisher=Huel}}</ref> \n* '''Flavour Boosts''' - Huel also sells Flavour Boosts. These have no nutritional value and are designed to complement Huel Powder mixes. Eleven flavours of Flavour Boosts are available from Huel.\n* '''Huel Bars''' - Launched in 2017, the snack bars are vegan and gluten-free.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://huel.com/products/huel-bar | title=Huel Bars | publisher=Huel}}</ref> Huel Bars are made up of 36% carbohydrates, 35% fat, 24% protein, and 5% fibre.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://huel.com/pages/the-huel-bar-formula-explained | title=The Huel Bars Formula Explained | publisher=Huel}}</ref>\n* '''Huel Granola''' - Introduced in 2018, Huel Granola is composed primarily of rolled oats.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://uk.huel.com/pages/the-huel-granola-formula | title=The Huel Granola Formula | publisher=Huel}}</ref>\n\n==Reviews and reception==\nIn March 2016, an article in Coach magazine described Huel\u2019s basic flavour as \u201cunderwhelming\u201d, though the reviewer did note that the taste can be improved substantially with Flavour Boosts and home recipes.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.coachmag.co.uk/nutrition/5161/is-huel-the-future-of-food | title=Is Huel the Future of Food? | first=NICK | last=HARRIS-FRY | work=Coach Magazine | date=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, after a week-long Huel-only diet, journalist Peter Robinson wrote, \"there are lumps in the mixture\" and stated, \"Huel doesn\u2019t just sound like the act of vomiting, it actually feels like doing it backwards\".<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/may/09/lunch-fatigue-meal-replacement-powder-huel | title=My week on powdered food made me feel less spaceman, more idiot | last=Robinson | first=Peter | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Jared Hill said after a week-long Huel-only diet \"I had finally freed myself from the shackles of food consumption, and let me tell you, it felt amazing.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://medium.com/@jamchiller/one-week-on-huel-one-small-step-for-man-one-giant-leap-for-my-bowels-a9026a48d94d | title=A Week on Huel: One Small Step for Man, One Giant Leap for My Bowels | first=Jared | last=Hill | work=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] | date=September 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, after a week-long trial, Tom Ough, a journalist for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described his Huel-only diet as \"struggling to get enough down me to hit anywhere near my 2000-calorie RDA,\" saying, \"I got bored of having the same thing all the time, but have lost well over three kilos despite finding it filling. I've also felt healthy throughout the experiment.\"<ref name=live/> He concluded that Huel was \"very good\", but better when used only occasionally.<ref name=live/>\n\nIn July 2017, Huel was referred to as \"Hipster Gruel\" by [[Dave Gorman]] on ''[[Dave Gorman: Modern Life is Goodish]]''.<ref>{{cite AV media | url=https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x5t4wo8 | title=Dave Gorman- Modern Life is Goodish S4 E6 | via=[[Dailymotion]] | date=July 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, ''[[Forbes]]'' listed Huel amongst the best \u201cgadgets to keep you fit and healthy\u201d.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/leebelltech/2018/03/26/the-best-health-tech-2017/ | title=Best Health Tech: Gadgets to Help Keep You Fit And Healthy | first=Lee | last=Bell | work=[[Forbes]] | date=6 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Liquid diet]]\n* [[Meal replacement]]\n* [[Protein shake]]\n* [[Therapeutic food]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://huel.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Dietary supplements]]\n[[Category:Nutritional supplement companies]]\n[[Category:Veganism]]\n[[Category:Vegetarian diets]]\n", "name_user": "Eidoom", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Fix up grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Huel"}
{"title_page": "Glee (season 4)", "text_new": "{{short description|2012\u201313 season of American musical comedy-drama}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox television season\n| season_number        = 4\n| bgcolour             = #56C8BA\n| image                = Glee Season 4 DVD.jpg\n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = Promotional poster and home media cover art\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Chris Colfer]]\n* [[Darren Criss]]\n* [[Jane Lynch]]\n* [[Kevin McHale (actor)|Kevin McHale]]\n* [[Lea Michele]]\n* [[Cory Monteith]]\n* [[Heather Morris]]\n* [[Matthew Morrison]]\n* [[Chord Overstreet]]\n* [[Amber Riley]]\n* [[Naya Rivera]]\n* [[Mark Salling]]\n* [[Harry Shum, Jr.]]\n* [[Jenna Ushkowitz]]}}\n| country              = United States\n| num_episodes         = 22\n| network              = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2012|9|13}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2013|5|9}}\n| episode_list         = List of Glee episodes\n}}\nThe fourth season of the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] musical [[comedy-drama]] television series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' was commissioned on April 9, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2012/04/09/fox-renews-glee-season-4-new-girl-season-2/|title=Breaking: Fox Renews ''Glee'', ''New Girl'' and ''Raising Hope''|first=Michael|last=Ausiello|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[PMC (company)|PMC]]|date=April 9, 2012|accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release|url=http://www.foxflash.com/div.php/main/page?aID=1z2z2z336z1z8&ID=8547|title=\"New Girl\", \"Raising Hope\" and \"Glee\" to continue laughs in 2012\u201313 season on Fox|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company]]|date=April 9, 2012|accessdate=April 11, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120630070603/http://www.foxflash.com/div.php/main/page?aID=1z2z2z336z1z8&ID=8547|archivedate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> It premiered on September 13, 2012 and is produced by [[20th Century Fox Television]], Ryan Murphy Television and Brad Falchuk Teley-Vision with executive producers [[Dante Di Loreto]] and series co-creators [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]], [[Brad Falchuk]] and [[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]].<ref name=\"FoxFall12\"/>\n\nThe series features the New Directions [[glee club]] at the fictional William McKinley High School in the town of [[Lima, Ohio]]. The fourth season continues in Lima with a new generation of students but will also follow some of the McKinley graduates from the third season, notably to the fictional New York Academy of the Dramatic Arts (NYADA) in New York City. The season follows the club competing on the show choir circuit, while its members, faculty and alumni deal with [[Adolescent sexuality|sex]], [[bulimia nervosa|bulimia]], [[gender identity]], [[child sexual abuse|child molestation]], [[dyslexia]], [[school violence]], [[false pregnancy|pregnancy scares]] and other social issues. As of the season premiere, fourteen main cast members retained that status from the third season: glee club director [[Will Schuester]] ([[Matthew Morrison]]), cheerleading coach [[Sue Sylvester]] ([[Jane Lynch]]), glee club members [[Artie Abrams]] ([[Kevin McHale (actor)|Kevin McHale]]), [[Blaine Anderson]] ([[Darren Criss]]), [[Tina Cohen-Chang]] ([[Jenna Ushkowitz]]), and [[Brittany Pierce]] ([[Heather Morris]]), and graduates [[Rachel Berry]] ([[Lea Michele]]), [[Mike Chang]] ([[Harry Shum, Jr.]]), [[Finn Hudson]] ([[Cory Monteith]]), [[Kurt Hummel]] ([[Chris Colfer]]), [[Mercedes Jones]] ([[Amber Riley]]), [[Santana Lopez]] ([[Naya Rivera]]) and [[Puck (Glee)|Noah \"Puck\" Puckerman]] ([[Mark Salling]]). Previously recurring character [[Sam Evans]] ([[Chord Overstreet]]), a glee club member, was promoted to the main cast in the fourth season. <!--Do not add Brody/Dean or Jake/Jacob for reasons given the \"Cast\" section below; also, leave off Joe, Sugar, Unique and Rory: reliable sources have established that the first three are recurring, and Rory, if he returns at all, won't do so until late 2012. None are series regulars/central characters.-->\n\n[[Dianna Agron]], who played [[Quinn Fabray]], appeared less frequently in the season than in previous ones, as did some of the other graduates, including [[Mercedes Jones]] (Amber Riley), [[Mike Chang]] (Harry Shum Jr.), and [[Noah Puckerman]] (Mark Salling), despite still being credited as main cast members for this season.<ref name=\"Keck723\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/KecksExclusives/status/227482997715243008|title=@KecksExclusives Don't think we'll be seeing much of @MsAmberPRiley @iharryshum @DiannaAgron and @MarkSalling on #glee new season, FOX suggests |first=William|last=Keck|work=Twitter|date=July 23, 2012|accessdate=July 23, 2012}}</ref> Agron and [[Jayma Mays]], who continued to appear as guidance counselor [[Emma Pillsbury]], were credited as guest stars this season rather than as series regulars.\n\nThis season marked the final appearance of [[Cory Monteith]] on the show before his death on July 13, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/438860/cory-monteith-found-dead|title=Cory Monteith found dead|accessdate=July 13, 2013|date=July 14, 2013|work=E! Online}}</ref> The season was nominated for four [[Primetime Emmy Awards]] including one for Lynch's performance as Sue Sylvester and the [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]].\n\n==Episodes==\n{{See also|List of Glee episodes}}\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Episode table |background=#56C8BA |overall=4 |season=4 |title=22 |director=14 |writer=27 |airdate=13 |prodcode=6 |viewers=10 |country=US |episodes=\n{{Episode list/sublist|Glee (season 4)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 67\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = [[The New Rachel]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Brad Falchuk]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|9|13}}\n| ProdCode        = 4ARC01\n| Viewers         = 7.41<ref name=\"glee4x01\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/09/14/thursday-final-ratings-glee-adjusted-down-no-adjustment-for-the-x-factor/148647/ |title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'Glee' Adjusted Down, No 18-49 Adjustment for 'The X-Factor' |last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda |work=TV by the Numbers|date=September 14, 2012 |accessdate=September 15, 2012}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = [[Rachel Berry|Rachel]] begins school at NYADA, where she meets junior Brody Weston ([[Dean Geyer]]) and starts classes with a tough dance instructor, Cassandra July ([[Kate Hudson]]). At McKinley High, the rebuilding of New Directions begins and [[Wade \"Unique\" Adams]] ([[Alex Newell]]) transfers to join the group. [[Kurt Hummel|Kurt]] aids director [[Will Schuester]] in finding potential recruits, who include [[Marley Rose]] ([[Melissa Benoist]]) and [[Puck (Glee)|Puck]]'s half brother [[Jake Puckerman|Jake]] ([[Jacob Artist]]).\n| LineColor       = 56C8BA\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Glee (season 4)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 68\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = [[Britney 2.0]]\n| WrittenBy       = Brad Falchuk\n| DirectedBy      = [[Alfonso Gomez-Rejon]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2012|9|20}}\n| ProdCode        = 4ARC02\n| Viewers         = 7.46<ref name=\"glee4x02\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/09/21/thursday-final-ratingsthe-x-factor-adjusted-up-wipeout-the-next-adjusted-down/149622/|title=Thursday Final Ratings:'The X Factor' Adjusted Up; 'Wipeout', 'The Next' Adjusted Down|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Bibel|first=Sara|date=September 21, 2012|accessdate=September 22, 2012}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = [[Brittany Pierce|Brittany]] is depressed, and turns to her namesake [[Britney Spears]] for inspiration, leading to the Glee Club and [[Sam Evans|Sam]] to help her out. Rachel continues to struggle in adjusting to life at NYADA and in New York, as well as the constant tormenting of Cassandra, but gets help from new friend and classmate Brody. Puck returns when Will calls him and meets Jake for the first time as he gives him an attitude adjustment.\n| LineColor       = 56C8BA\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Glee (season 4)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 69\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           =  [[Makeover (Glee)|Makeover]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Ian Brennan (writer)|Ian Brennan]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Eric Stoltz]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2012|9|27}}\n| ProdCode        = 4ARC03\n| Viewers         = 5.79<ref name=\"glee4x03\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/09/28/thursday-final-ratings-big-bang-theory-greys-anatomy-adjusted-up-parks-rec-up-all-night-snl-weekend-update-the-office-glee-scandal-rock-center-adjust/150556/|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'Big Bang Theory', 'Grey's Anatomy', Adjusted Up; 'Parks & Rec.', 'Up All Night', 'SNL: Weekend Update', 'The Office', 'Glee', 'Scandal', 'Rock Center' Adjusted Down|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|date=September 28, 2012|accessdate=September 29, 2012}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = At McKinley High, [[Blaine Anderson|Blaine]] and Sam run against Brittany and [[Artie Abrams|Artie]] for the student council, and win. Kurt gets an internship in New York at Vogue.com, working for Isabelle Wright ([[Sarah Jessica Parker]]) and excels, while he is inadvertently pulling away from Blaine. Rachel starts to warm up to her new classmate Brody and invites him to her and Kurt's apartment just as her former fianc\u00e9 [[Finn Hudson|Finn]] shows up there unexpectedly.\n| LineColor       = 56C8BA\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Glee (season 4)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 70\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = [[The Break Up (Glee)|The Break Up]]\n| WrittenBy       = Ryan Murphy\n| DirectedBy      = Alfonso Gomez-Rejon\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2012|10|4}}\n| ProdCode        = 4ARC04\n| Viewers         = 6.07<ref name=\"glee4x04\">{{cite web