{"title_page": "2020 Salvadoran political crisis", "text_new": "{{Infobox civil conflict\n| title            = 2020 Salvadoran political crisis\n| subtitle         = \n| partof           = \n| image            = 1,400 SOLDADOS SE INCORPORAN A PLAN CONTROL TERRITORIAL.jpg\n| caption          = President [[Nayib Bukele]] and 1,400 Salvadoran soldiers in front of the [[National Palace (El Salvador)|National Palace of El Salvador]].\n| date             = February 9, 2020\n| place            = [[El Salvador]]\n| coordinates      = \n| causes           = \n| goals            = Pressure politicians to approve a 109 million dollar loan for a security plan<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/constitutional-crisis-el-salvador-bukele-security-plan-200210183636678.html|title=Constitutional crisis in El Salvador over Bukele's security plan|date=February 10, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n| methods          = Troop entry into the [[Legislative Assembly of El Salvador|Legislative Assembly]], political intimidation\n| status           = Developing\n| result           = Demonstrations, possible breakdown of constitutional order and democracy\n| side1            = {{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[El Salvador|Salvadoran Government]]<br />{{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Armed Forces of El Salvador]]<br />{{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[National Civil Police of El Salvador|National Civil Police]]<br />Public workers<br />'''International support:'''<br />{{flagicon|Guatemala}} [[Guatemala]]{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n| side2            = {{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Legislative Assembly of El Salvador|Legislative Assembly]]<br />'''Political support:'''<br />[[File:Alianza Republicana Nacionalista.svg|23px|border]] [[Nationalist Republican Alliance|ARENA]]<br />[[File:Frente Farabundo Mart\u00ed para la Liberaci\u00f3n Nacional.svg|23px|border]] [[Farabundo Mart\u00ed National Liberation Front|FMLN]]<br />'''Legal support:'''<br />{{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Supreme Court of El Salvador]]\n| side3            = \n| side4            = \n| leadfigures1     = {{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Nayib Bukele]]\n| leadfigures2     = {{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Mario Ponce]]\n| leadfigures3     = \n| leadfigures4     = \n| howmany1         = \n| howmany2         = \n| howmany3         = \n| howmany4         = \n| casualties1      = \n| casualties2      = \n| casualties3      = \n| casualties4      = \n| fatalities       =\n| injuries         =\n| arrests          =\n| detentions       =\n| charged          =\n| fined            =\n| effect           =\n| effect_label     =\n| casualties_label = \n| notes            = \n| sidebox          = \n}}\n\n{{Politics of El Salvador}}\n\nThe '''2020 Salvadoran political crisis''' was a brief occurrence on February 9, 2020, where Salvadoran President [[Nayib Bukele]] ordered 1,400 Salvadoran soldiers from the [[Salvadoran Army]] to enter the [[Legislative Assembly of El Salvador]] in order to intimidate politicians to request a loan of 109 million dollars from the [[United States]] to be given to Bukele's security plan for [[El Salvador]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-51440009|title=Crisis en El Salvador: cu\u00e1les son los motivos de la fuerte tensi\u00f3n entre el presidente Nayib Bukele y el Congreso|date=February 10, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n\nPrior to the crisis, President Nayib Bukele wanted a loan of 109 million dollars from the [[United States]] so he can use the money to improve the [[National Civil Police of El Salvador]] and the [[Armed Forces of El Salvador]] in what he calls the \"[[Territorial Control Plan]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dsm.forecastinternational.com/wordpress/2020/02/11/assembly-standoff-leads-to-crisis-in-el-salvador/|title=Assembly Standoff Leads to Crisis in El Salvador|date=February 11, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> On February 7, Bukele, under the protection of numeral 7 of article 167 of the [[Constitution of El Salvador]], called on the [[Council of Ministers (El Salvador)|Council of Ministers]] to convene in the Legislative Assembly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.laprensagrafica.com/elsalvador/Por-que-El-Salvador-se-encuentra-ante-el-precipicio-20200214-0029.html|title=\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 El Salvador se encuentra ante el precipicio?|date=February 14, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Crisis ==\n\nOn February 8, President Bukele again made use of the Constitution by invoking the use of article 87, authorizing a popular insurrection in case of breaking the constitutional order, although, it was not broken.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telesurtv.net/news/nayib-bukele-presiona-diputados-prestamo-seguridad-el-salvador-20200208-0010.html|title=El Salvador: Bukele amenaza a diputados para conseguir pr\u00e9stamo|date=February 8, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 9, Bukele,, entered into the Blue Room and sat in the chair of Assembly President [[Mario Ponce]]. The next day, the [[Supreme Court of El Salvador]] prohibited the President from calling the Legislative Assembly, also prohibited all public forces, including the Ministry of Defense, from exercising functions other than those allowed by the Constitution. Bukele expressed dissatisfaction with the order and stated that \"the system protects itself\u201d, but abided by the Supreme Court\u2019s decision. \n\n== Reactions ==\n\nSmall demonstrations against Bukele were reported, mainly grouped at the [[University of El Salvador]] (UES) in San Salvador.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.efe.com/efe/america/politica/debiles-protestas-contra-la-actuacion-de-bukele-en-el-congreso-salvadoreno/20000035-4172493|title=D\u00e9biles protestas contra la actuaci\u00f3n de Bukele en el Congreso salvadore\u00f1o|date=February 13, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> [[Amnesty International]] and [[Human Rights Watch]] described the actions of the President as \"dangerous\" and \"serious,\" respectively. [[Citation needed|<sup>[citation needed]</sup>]] \n\nOpposition parties of both the right, the [[Nationalist Republican Alliance]] (ARENA), and the left, the [[Farabundo Mart\u00ed National Liberation Front]] (FMLN), accused the entry of troops as a [[self-coup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telesurtv.net/news/nayib-bukele-presiona-diputados-prestamo-seguridad-el-salvador-20200208-0010.html|title=Corte Suprema de Justicia de El Salvador proh\u00edbe al presidente convocar al Parlamento|date=February 15, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> Bukele denied the claims of a self-coup stating that \"if I was a dictator, I would have taken control of everything.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-51458947|title=El Salvador parliament denounces president's 'attempted coup'|date=February 11, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> The FMLN accused that several of its parliamentarians were harassed by the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elmundo.sv/fmln-recopila-denuncias-por-persecucion-contra-diputados/|title=FMLN recopila denuncias por persecuci\u00f3n contra diputados|date=February 13, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> The FMLN also stated it will ask for an appeal against [[Francis Merino]] (Minister of Defense) and [[Rogelio Rivas (Salvadoran politician)|Rogelio Rivas]] (Justice and Security of the Public) for their participation in the crisis on February 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elmundo.sv/fmln-pide-interpelar-a-rivas-y-merino-arena-aun-evalua/|title=FMLN pide interpelar a Rivas y Merino, Arena a\u00fan eval\u00faa|date=February 14, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 24, Monsignor [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Escobar Alas]], President of the [[Episcopal Conference of El Salvador]] and the [[Archbishop of San Salvador]], asked people to \"lower the tone of mutual attacks, or one for the other, because in this way we cannot move forward, because in the end the one that is affected is the people to avoid a new conflict,\" in reference to the [[Salvadoran Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.europapress.es/internacional/noticia-iglesia-llama-bajar-tono-crisis-politica-salvador-evitar-nuevo-conflicto-20200224140807.html|title=La Iglesia llama a \"bajar el tono\" ante la crisis pol\u00edtica en El Salvador para evitar un nuevo conflicto|date=February 24, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Salvadoran Civil War]]\n* [[Politics of El Salvador]]\n* [[President of El Salvador]]\n* [[Armed Forces of El Salvador]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Presidents of El Salvador]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox civil conflict\n| title            = 2020 Salvadoran political crisis\n| subtitle         = \n| partof           = \n| image            = 1,400 SOLDADOS SE INCORPORAN A PLAN CONTROL TERRITORIAL.jpg\n| caption          = President [[Nayib Bukele]] and 1,400 Salvadoran soldiers in front of the [[National Palace (El Salvador)|National Palace of El Salvador]].\n| date             = February 9, 2020\n| place            = [[El Salvador]]\n| coordinates      = \n| causes           = \n| goals            = Pressure politicians to approve a 109 million dollar loan for a security plan<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/constitutional-crisis-el-salvador-bukele-security-plan-200210183636678.html|title=Constitutional crisis in El Salvador over Bukele's security plan|date=February 10, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n| methods          = Troop entry into the [[Legislative Assembly of El Salvador|Legislative Assembly]], political intimidation\n| status           = Developing\n| result           = Demonstrations, possible breakdown of constitutional order and democracy\n| side1            = {{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[El Salvador|Salvadoran Government]]<br />{{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Armed Forces of El Salvador]]<br />{{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[National Civil Police of El Salvador|National Civil Police]]<br />Public workers<br />'''International support:'''<br />{{flagicon|Guatemala}} [[Guatemala]]{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n| side2            = {{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Legislative Assembly of El Salvador|Legislative Assembly]]<br />'''Political support:'''<br />[[File:Alianza Republicana Nacionalista.svg|23px|border]] [[Nationalist Republican Alliance|ARENA]]<br />[[File:Frente Farabundo Mart\u00ed para la Liberaci\u00f3n Nacional.svg|23px|border]] [[Farabundo Mart\u00ed National Liberation Front|FMLN]]<br />'''Legal support:'''<br />{{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Supreme Court of El Salvador]]\n| side3            = \n| side4            = \n| leadfigures1     = {{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Nayib Bukele]]\n| leadfigures2     = {{flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Mario Ponce]]\n| leadfigures3     = \n| leadfigures4     = \n| howmany1         = \n| howmany2         = \n| howmany3         = \n| howmany4         = \n| casualties1      = \n| casualties2      = \n| casualties3      = \n| casualties4      = \n| fatalities       =\n| injuries         =\n| arrests          =\n| detentions       =\n| charged          =\n| fined            =\n| effect           =\n| effect_label     =\n| casualties_label = \n| notes            = \n| sidebox          = \n}}\n\n{{Politics of El Salvador}}\n\nThe '''2020 Salvadoran political crisis''' was a brief occurrence on February 9, 2020, where Salvadoran President [[Nayib Bukele]] ordered 1,400 Salvadoran soldiers from the [[Salvadoran Army]] to enter the [[Legislative Assembly of El Salvador]] in order to intimidate politicians to request a loan of 109 million dollars from the [[United States]] to be given to Bukele's security plan for [[El Salvador]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-51440009|title=Crisis en El Salvador: cu\u00e1les son los motivos de la fuerte tensi\u00f3n entre el presidente Nayib Bukele y el Congreso|date=February 10, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n\nPrior to the crisis, President Nayib Bukele wanted a loan of 109 million dollars from the [[United States]] so he can use the money to improve the [[National Civil Police of El Salvador]] and the [[Armed Forces of El Salvador]] in what he calls the \"[[Territorial Control Plan]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dsm.forecastinternational.com/wordpress/2020/02/11/assembly-standoff-leads-to-crisis-in-el-salvador/|title=Assembly Standoff Leads to Crisis in El Salvador|date=February 11, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> On February 7, Bukele, under the protection of numeral 7 of article 167 of the [[Constitution of El Salvador]], called on the [[Council of Ministers (El Salvador)|Council of Ministers]] to convene in the Legislative Assembly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.laprensagrafica.com/elsalvador/Por-que-El-Salvador-se-encuentra-ante-el-precipicio-20200214-0029.html|title=\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 El Salvador se encuentra ante el precipicio?|date=February 14, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Crisis ==\n\nOn February 8, President Bukele again made use of the Constitution by invoking the use of article 87, authorizing a popular insurrection in case of breaking the constitutional order, although, it was not broken.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telesurtv.net/news/nayib-bukele-presiona-diputados-prestamo-seguridad-el-salvador-20200208-0010.html|title=El Salvador: Bukele amenaza a diputados para conseguir pr\u00e9stamo|date=February 8, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 9, Bukele,, entered into the Blue Room and sat in the chair of Assembly President [[Mario Ponce]]. The next day, the [[Supreme Court of El Salvador]] prohibited the President from calling the Legislative Assembly, also prohibited all public forces, including the Ministry of Defense, from exercising functions other than those allowed by the Constitution. Bukele expressed dissatisfaction with the order by stating that \"the system protects itself\u201d, but abided by the Supreme Court\u2019s decision. \n\n== Reactions ==\n\nSmall demonstrations against Bukele were reported, mainly grouped at the [[University of El Salvador]] (UES) in San Salvador.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.efe.com/efe/america/politica/debiles-protestas-contra-la-actuacion-de-bukele-en-el-congreso-salvadoreno/20000035-4172493|title=D\u00e9biles protestas contra la actuaci\u00f3n de Bukele en el Congreso salvadore\u00f1o|date=February 13, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> [[Amnesty International]] and [[Human Rights Watch]] described the actions of the President as \"dangerous\" and \"serious,\" respectively. [[Citation needed|<sup>[citation needed]</sup>]] \n\nOpposition parties of both the right, the [[Nationalist Republican Alliance]] (ARENA), and the left, the [[Farabundo Mart\u00ed National Liberation Front]] (FMLN), accused the entry of troops as a [[self-coup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telesurtv.net/news/nayib-bukele-presiona-diputados-prestamo-seguridad-el-salvador-20200208-0010.html|title=Corte Suprema de Justicia de El Salvador proh\u00edbe al presidente convocar al Parlamento|date=February 15, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> Bukele denied the claims of a self-coup stating that \"if I was a dictator, I would have taken control of everything.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-51458947|title=El Salvador parliament denounces president's 'attempted coup'|date=February 11, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> The FMLN accused that several of its parliamentarians were harassed by the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elmundo.sv/fmln-recopila-denuncias-por-persecucion-contra-diputados/|title=FMLN recopila denuncias por persecuci\u00f3n contra diputados|date=February 13, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> The FMLN also stated it will ask for an appeal against [[Francis Merino]] (Minister of Defense) and [[Rogelio Rivas (Salvadoran politician)|Rogelio Rivas]] (Justice and Security of the Public) for their participation in the crisis on February 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elmundo.sv/fmln-pide-interpelar-a-rivas-y-merino-arena-aun-evalua/|title=FMLN pide interpelar a Rivas y Merino, Arena a\u00fan eval\u00faa|date=February 14, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 24, Monsignor [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Escobar Alas]], President of the [[Episcopal Conference of El Salvador]] and the [[Archbishop of San Salvador]], asked people to \"lower the tone of mutual attacks, or one for the other, because in this way we cannot move forward, because in the end the one that is affected is the people to avoid a new conflict,\" in reference to the [[Salvadoran Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.europapress.es/internacional/noticia-iglesia-llama-bajar-tono-crisis-politica-salvador-evitar-nuevo-conflicto-20200224140807.html|title=La Iglesia llama a \"bajar el tono\" ante la crisis pol\u00edtica en El Salvador para evitar un nuevo conflicto|date=February 24, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Salvadoran Civil War]]\n* [[Politics of El Salvador]]\n* [[President of El Salvador]]\n* [[Armed Forces of El Salvador]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Presidents of El Salvador]]\n", "name_user": "Researcher29", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Salvadoran_political_crisis"}
{"title_page": "Charles Christie (officer)", "text_new": "'''Charles Christie''' (died 1812) was a British officer, mostly remembered for his endeavours in [[Qajar Iran]]. He was the son of [[James Christie]] the Auctioneer.<ref> M.A. Michael (2019). \"[https://www.academia.edu/40805885/_Not_exactly_a_connoisseur_A_new_portrait_of_James_Christie_by_Benjamin_Vandergucht_1752_1794_and_the_auctioneer_s_family_history Not Exactly a Connoisseur A New Portrait of James Christie]\". ''The British Art Journal'' (London: Robin Simon).''' 19''':76.</ref>. (2019)  A member of the first British military mission to Iran (1810), he was killed in action while serving on the Iranian side during the [[Russo-Persian War (1804\u20131813)|Russo-Persian War of 1804\u20131813]].\n\n==Biography==\nOriginally a captain of the [[103rd Regiment of Foot (Royal Bombay Fusiliers)|Bombay Regiment]] of the Anglo-Indian army, in 1810, Christie and Lieutenant [[Henry Pottinger]] were ordered by Sir [[John Malcolm]] to explore the route from [[Bombay]] to [[Baluchistan]], [[Sistan]] and the [[Makran]]. These areas were thought to hold a possible overland route by which a European army could invade India.{{sfn|Ekbal|1991|pages=547\u2013548}} Christie and Pottinger disguised themselves as horse dealers, and travelled north from the Makran coast to [[Nushki]], where the two separated in March&nbsp;1810. Christie moved north through Sistan to [[Herat]] and thereafter across the central Iranian desert to [[Yazd]] and [[Isfahan]]. A manuscript of Christie's travel journal is appended to Pottingers account of his expedition, which provided the first reliable information about these territories.{{sfn|Ekbal|1991|pages=547\u2013548}}\n\nAt the request of [[Harford Jones-Brydges]], the British envoy to Iran, Christie and a number of other officers entered the Iranian military service, forming the core of the military mission provided for in accordance with the Preliminary Treaty of Friendship and Alliance that Jones-Brydges had negotiated with [[Fath-Ali Shah Qajar]] ({{reign}}1797\u20131834) on&nbsp;17 June 1809.{{sfn|Cronin|2011}}{{sfn|Ekbal|1991|pages=547\u2013548}}\n\nChristie was ordered with training the Iranian infantry (''sarbaz'') and became the commander of the [[Shaqaqi]] Regiment, one of the twelve new regiments (''Nezam-e Jadid'') in the province of [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]]. Christie fought on the Iranian side against the [[Russian Empire|Russians]] during the [[Russo-Persian War (1804\u20131813)|Russo-Persian War of 1804\u20131813]]. However, in 1812, Britain and Russia had reconciled, which meant that Britain was withdrawing its support from Iran. Christie, two other British officers ([[Henry Lindsay Bethune|Henry Lindsay]] and [[William Monteith]]) and thirteen sergeants were allowed to remain in the Iranian service at the request of Crown Prince [[Abbas Mirza]], commander of the Iranian army. Christie and Lindsay both participated in the [[Battle of Sultanabad]] (13&nbsp;February 1812), in which the Iranian army achieved a victory.{{sfn|Atkin|1980|page=137}} During the battle, Christie and Lindsay reportedly threw themselves into the thick of it, thereby gaining the admiration of the Iranians and proving that they would not refrain from attacking fellow Christians.{{sfn|Atkin|1980|page=137}}{{sfn|Ekbal|1991|pages=547\u2013548}}\n\nBoth also participated in the ensuing [[Battle of Aslanduz]] (31 October\u20131 November 1812), in which the Iranians suffered a major defeat. During the battle, Christie was shot in the neck, but, as he refused to surrender, was said to have killed six Russian soldiers before being killed himself.{{sfn|Ekbal|1991|pages=547\u2013548}} John Cormick, physician to Abbas Mirza, found Christie's remains and buried them near the spot where he had been killed.{{sfn|Ekbal|1991|pages=547\u2013548}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last1=Atkin|first1=Muriel|title=Russia and Iran, 1780\u20131828|date=1980|publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]]|isbn=978-0816609246|ref=harv}}\n* {{ cite encyclopedia | title = ARMY v. Qajar Period ii. Early Qajar military reform. | last = Cronin | first = Stephanie | authorlink = | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/army-v | editor-last = | editor-first =  | editor-link = | encyclopedia  = Encyclopaedia Iranica | pages = | location = | publisher = | year = 2011 | isbn = |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | title = Christie, Charles | last = Ekbal | first = Kamran | authorlink = | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/christie-captain-charles-d | editor-last = | editor-first =  | editor-link = | encyclopedia  = Encyclopaedia Iranica, Vol. V, Fasc. 5 | pages = 547\u2013548 | location = | publisher = | year = 1991 | isbn = |ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:18th-century births]]\n[[Category:1812 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century British Army personnel]]\n[[Category:People of the Russo-Persian Wars]]\n[[Category:Qajar dynasty]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in Iran]]\n[[Category:British East India Company Army officers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Charles Christie''' (died 1812) was a British officer, mostly remembered for his endeavours in [[Qajar Iran]]. A member of the first British military mission to Iran (1810), he was killed in action while serving on the Iranian side during the [[Russo-Persian War (1804\u20131813)|Russo-Persian War of 1804\u20131813]].\n\n==Biography==\nOriginally a captain of the [[103rd Regiment of Foot (Royal Bombay Fusiliers)|Bombay Regiment]] of the Anglo-Indian army, in 1810, Christie and Lieutenant [[Henry Pottinger]] were ordered by Sir [[John Malcolm]] to explore the route from [[Bombay]] to [[Baluchistan]], [[Sistan]] and the [[Makran]]. These areas were thought to hold a possible overland route by which a European army could invade India.{{sfn|Ekbal|1991|pages=547\u2013548}} Christie and Pottinger disguised themselves as horse dealers, and travelled north from the Makran coast to [[Nushki]], where the two separated in March&nbsp;1810. Christie moved north through Sistan to [[Herat]] and thereafter across the central Iranian desert to [[Yazd]] and [[Isfahan]]. A manuscript of Christie's travel journal is appended to Pottingers account of his expedition, which provided the first reliable information about these territories.{{sfn|Ekbal|1991|pages=547\u2013548}}\n\nAt the request of [[Harford Jones-Brydges]], the British envoy to Iran, Christie and a number of other officers entered the Iranian military service, forming the core of the military mission provided for in accordance with the Preliminary Treaty of Friendship and Alliance that Jones-Brydges had negotiated with [[Fath-Ali Shah Qajar]] ({{reign}}1797\u20131834) on&nbsp;17 June 1809.{{sfn|Cronin|2011}}{{sfn|Ekbal|1991|pages=547\u2013548}}\n\nChristie was ordered with training the Iranian infantry (''sarbaz'') and became the commander of the [[Shaqaqi]] Regiment, one of the twelve new regiments (''Nezam-e Jadid'') in the province of [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]]. Christie fought on the Iranian side against the [[Russian Empire|Russians]] during the [[Russo-Persian War (1804\u20131813)|Russo-Persian War of 1804\u20131813]]. However, in 1812, Britain and Russia had reconciled, which meant that Britain was withdrawing its support from Iran. Christie, two other British officers ([[Henry Lindsay Bethune|Henry Lindsay]] and [[William Monteith]]) and thirteen sergeants were allowed to remain in the Iranian service at the request of Crown Prince [[Abbas Mirza]], commander of the Iranian army. Christie and Lindsay both participated in the [[Battle of Sultanabad]] (13&nbsp;February 1812), in which the Iranian army achieved a victory.{{sfn|Atkin|1980|page=137}} During the battle, Christie and Lindsay reportedly threw themselves into the thick of it, thereby gaining the admiration of the Iranians and proving that they would not refrain from attacking fellow Christians.{{sfn|Atkin|1980|page=137}}{{sfn|Ekbal|1991|pages=547\u2013548}}\n\nBoth also participated in the ensuing [[Battle of Aslanduz]] (31 October\u20131 November 1812), in which the Iranians suffered a major defeat. During the battle, Christie was shot in the neck, but, as he refused to surrender, was said to have killed six Russian soldiers before being killed himself.{{sfn|Ekbal|1991|pages=547\u2013548}} John Cormick, physician to Abbas Mirza, found Christie's remains and buried them near the spot where he had been killed.{{sfn|Ekbal|1991|pages=547\u2013548}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last1=Atkin|first1=Muriel|title=Russia and Iran, 1780\u20131828|date=1980|publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]]|isbn=978-0816609246|ref=harv}}\n* {{ cite encyclopedia | title = ARMY v. Qajar Period ii. Early Qajar military reform. | last = Cronin | first = Stephanie | authorlink = | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/army-v | editor-last = | editor-first =  | editor-link = | encyclopedia  = Encyclopaedia Iranica | pages = | location = | publisher = | year = 2011 | isbn = |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | title = Christie, Charles | last = Ekbal | first = Kamran | authorlink = | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/christie-captain-charles-d | editor-last = | editor-first =  | editor-link = | encyclopedia  = Encyclopaedia Iranica, Vol. V, Fasc. 5 | pages = 547\u2013548 | location = | publisher = | year = 1991 | isbn = |ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:18th-century births]]\n[[Category:1812 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century British Army personnel]]\n[[Category:People of the Russo-Persian Wars]]\n[[Category:Qajar dynasty]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in Iran]]\n[[Category:British East India Company Army officers]]\n", "name_user": "Architaxiarchis2", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added biographical information. Added footnote to source of information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Christie_(officer)"}
{"title_page": "Canary trap", "text_new": "{{short description|Method for exposing an information leak by giving different versions of a sensitive document to each of several suspects}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}\nA '''canary trap''' is a method for exposing an information leak by giving different versions of a sensitive document to each of several suspects and seeing which version gets leaked. It could be one false statement, to see whether sensitive information gets out to other people as well. Special attention is paid to the quality of the prose of the unique language, in the hopes that the suspect will repeat it verbatim in the leak, thereby identifying the version of the document.\n\nThe term was coined by [[Tom Clancy]] in his novel ''[[Patriot Games]]'',<ref>{{Cite book|title=Patriot games|last=Clancy, Tom, 1947-2013.|isbn=9780440001034|oclc=1044632177}}</ref> although Clancy did not invent the technique. The actual method (usually referred to as a '''barium meal test''' in espionage circles) has been used by intelligence agencies for many years. The fictional character [[Jack Ryan (fictional character)|Jack Ryan]] describes the technique he devised for identifying the sources of leaked classified documents:\n\n<blockquote>\n''Each summary paragraph has six different versions, and the mixture of those paragraphs is unique to each numbered copy of the paper. There are over a thousand possible permutations, but only ninety-six numbered copies of the actual document. The reason the summary paragraphs are so lurid is to entice a reporter to quote them verbatim in the public media. If he quotes something from two or three of those paragraphs, we know which copy he saw and, therefore, who leaked it.'' </blockquote>\n\nA refinement of this technique uses a thesaurus program to shuffle through synonyms, thus making every copy of the document unique.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/nba-canary-trap-media-2014-12|title=The NBA Used An Espionage Trick Known As 'Canary Trap' To Catch Teams Leaking Info To The Media|last=Gaines|first=Cork|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\n==Known canary trap cases==\n\nFollowing the troubled production of ''[[Star Trek: The Motion Picture]]'' in the late 1970s, [[Paramount Pictures]] effectively replaced [[Gene Roddenberry]] as producer of [[Star Trek (film series)|further movies]] in the [[Media franchise|franchise]] with [[Harve Bennett]]. Roddenberry was retained as an \"executive consultant\", due to the high regard the series' fans held him in; while he had little real authority he was still kept involved in the creative process. The fans often complained about particular plot developments proposed for the films, such as the death of [[Spock]] in ''[[Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan|Star Trek II]]'', that Roddenberry had opposed. So, before any drafts of the screenplay for ''[[Star Trek III: The Search for Spock]]'' were circulated, Bennett arranged for each individual copy to have subtle clues distinguishing it from the others. Shortly after Roddenberry opposed the destruction of the ''[[USS Enterprise (NCC-1701)|Enterprise]]'' at the climax of that film, fans began to complain to Paramount and Bennett. He found that a leaked copy of the script was the one given to Roddenberry, but was unable to do anything about it.<ref name=\"Star Trek films\">{{cite book|last1=Engel|first1=Joel|authorlink1=|title=Gene Roddenberry: The Myth and the Man Behind ''Star Trek''|pages=[https://archive.org/details/generoddenberrym00enge/page/210 210\u201311]|date=1994|publisher=[[Hachette Books|Hyperion Books]]|isbn=0786860049|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/generoddenberrym00enge/page/210}}</ref>\n\nAfter a series of leaks at [[Tesla Motors]] in 2008, CEO [[Elon Musk]] reportedly sent slightly different versions of an e-mail to each employee in an attempt to reveal potential leakers. The e-mail was disguised as a request to employees to sign a new [[non-disclosure agreement]]. The plan was undermined when the company's general counsel forwarded his own unique version of the e-mail with the attached agreement. As a result, Musk's scheme was realized by employees who now had a safe copy to leak.<ref>{{cite web \n |url=http://gawker.com/5164035/tesla-ceo-in-digital-witch-hunt \n |author=Owen Thomas \n |year=2009 \n |title=Tesla CEO in Digital Witch Hunt \n |accessdate=2013-11-16 \n |publisher=[[Gawker Media]] \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020092330/http://gawker.com/5164035/tesla-ceo-in-digital-witch-hunt \n |archivedate=2013-10-20 \n }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, it was proposed as a method for the [[Presidency of Donald Trump| Trump Administration]] to catch leaks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/whats-in-sessions-toolkit-for-hunting-anti-trump-leakers|title=What's in Sessions' toolkit for hunting anti-Trump leakers?|last=Wallace|first=Christopher|date=2017-08-04|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, British celebrity [[Coleen Rooney]] used the technique to identify who was leaking information from her private [[Instagram]] stories to tabloid newspaper [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] by posting fake stories which were blocked to all but one account. When these details appeared in the press, she publicly identified the leaks as coming from the account of Rebekah Vardy, wife of footballer [[Jamie Vardy]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosseinsky |first1=Katie |year=2019 |title=Coleen Rooney accuses Rebekah Vardy's Instagram account of leaking stories to the press |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/colleen-rooney-accuses-rebekah-vardy-of-leaking-stories-about-her-a4257461.html |website=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=2019-10-09}}</ref>.\n\n==Barium meal test==\nAccording to the book ''[[Spycatcher]]''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Spycatcher|last=Wright, Peter, 1916-1995.|date=1989|publisher=Mandarin|isbn=1863300007|oclc=27626618}}</ref> by [[Peter Wright (MI5 officer)|Peter Wright]] (published in 1987) the technique is standard practice that has been used by [[MI5]] (and other intelligence agencies) for many years, under the name \"[[barium meal]] test\". A barium meal test is more sophisticated than a canary trap because it is flexible and may take many different forms. However, the basic premise is to reveal a secret to a suspected enemy (but nobody else) then monitor whether there is evidence of the fake information being utilised by the other side. For example, a suspected double agent could be offered some tempting \"bait\": e.g., be told that important information was stored at a [[dead drop]] site. The fake dead drop site could then be periodically checked for signs of disturbance. If the site showed signs of being disturbed (for instance, in order to copy microfilm stored there), then this would confirm that the suspected enemy really was an enemy, i.e., a double agent.\n\n==Embedding information==\nThe technique of embedding significant information in a hidden form in a medium has been used in many ways, which are usually classified according to intent:\n\n* [[Watermark]]s are used to show that items are authentic and not forged.\n* [[Steganography]] is used to hide a secret message in an apparently innocuous message, in order to escape detection.\n* A canary trap hides information in a document that uniquely identifies it, so that copies of it can be traced.\n* [[Screener (promotional)|Screener]] versions of DVDs are often marked in some way so as to allow the tracking of unauthorised releases to their source.\n* As with the ''Star Trek'' incident, major films or television productions frequently give out scripts to the cast and crew in which one or two lines are different in each individual version. Thus if the entire script is copied and leaked to the public, the producers can track down the specific person who leaked the script. In practice this does not prevent generalized information about the script from being leaked, but it does discourage leaking verbatim copies of the script itself.\n* [[Trap street]]s on maps, or intentionally fictitious streets, are sometimes included to track copyright violations by those who might republish copyrighted maps illegally.\n* [[Fictitious entry|Spurious words]] are sometimes included in dictionaries so as to detect other publishers copying from them. The [[OED]] contains an appendix of such words with which edition of which dictionary first used them and which first duplicated them.\n* [[Zero-width spaces]] are Unicode characters that are not visually rendered. An arbitrary number of these characters can be inserted betw&#8203;een the letters of a word. Though they are not visible, they will typically persist even as that word is copied and pasted and transmitted multiple times. This can be used to create persistent, invisible fingerprints in digital text.<ref>{{cite website|url=https://www.zachaysan.com/writing/2017-12-30-zero-width-characters|title=Zero-Width Characters - Invisibly fingerprinting text|author=Zach Aysan}}</ref>\n* [[Mailing lists]] for purchase are typically seeded with a small number of postal or e-mail addresses that route back to the seller of the list. This is used to detect re-use of the list (typically sold on a per-mailing basis) or resale of the list (usually prohibited).\n\n==In popular culture==\n\n* The canary trap was used in several of Tom Clancy's novels.  Chronologically it first appears in ''[[Without Remorse]]'', when a CIA official alters a report given to a senator, revealing an internal leak who was giving information to the [[KGB]].  Different versions of the report were given to other suspected leakers.\n* Barium meals are also administered in Robert Littel's book ''[[The Company (Littell novel)|The Company]]'', and later in the TV miniseries with same name.\n* The technique (not named) was used in the 1970s BBC television serial ''[[1990 (TV series)|1990]]''.  The same unnamed technique also appeared in [[Irving Wallace]]'s book ''[[The Word (novel)|The Word]]'' (1972).\n* A variation of the canary trap was used in the film ''[[Miami Vice (film)|Miami Vice]]'', with various rendezvous dates leaked to different groups.\n* In the [[Strawberries and Cream (The Mentalist)|third-season finale]] of ''[[The Mentalist]]'', the characters use a canary trap (giving different hotel room numbers to different suspects) to uncover a [[Mole (espionage)|mole]] within their agency. A similar ruse is used in the TV series ''[[Ashes to Ashes (TV series)|Ashes to Ashes]]''.\n* In ''[[A Clash of Kings]]'', the second book in the [[A Song of Ice and Fire]] series, [[Tyrion Lannister]] uses the trap to find out which member of the King's [[Privy Council]] is reporting to his sister, the Queen Regent [[Cersei Lannister]]. To the Grand Maester Pycelle, he tells of a plot to marry his niece, [[Myrcella Baratheon|Princess Myrcella]], to Prince [[Trystane Martell|Trystane]] of the powerful [[House Martell]], from [[Dorne]]. To [[Petyr Baelish|Littlefinger]], he claims he will instead send Myrcella to be raised by [[Lysa Arryn]] and married to her son Robert. To [[Varys]], he says his plan is to send his nephew [[Tommen Baratheon|Tommen]] to the Martells. When Cersei confronts him, and knows only of the plan to send Myrcella to Dorne, Tyrion knows Pycelle to be the leak.\n** This plotline is also depicted in \"[[What Is Dead May Never Die]]\", during [[Game of Thrones (season 2)|the second season]] of ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', the television adaptation of the books.\n* When distributing the film ''[[Broken (1993 film)|Broken]]'' to friends, [[Trent Reznor]] claims that he watermarked the tapes with dropouts at certain points so that he could identify if a leak would surface.\n* In the film ''[[The Heat (film)|The Heat]]'' starring Melissa McCarthy and Sandra Bullock, a canary trap is employed by a drug ring to decide the loyalty of a returning member who is detective Mullins' brother.\n* In ''Han Solo at Stars' End'', the first book in ''[[The Han Solo Adventures]]'', the title character uses a canary trap to find a traitor and murderer among his passengers.  He tells each that their target is a different planet, all false, knowing that the traitor would have learned the real destination when they killed the group's leader.\n\n==See also==\n*{{annotated link|Recruitment of spies|aka=Clandestine HUMINT asset recruiting}}\n*{{annotated link|Coded anti-piracy}}\n*{{annotated link|Fictitious entry}}\n*{{annotated link|Honeytoken}}\n*{{annotated link|Machine Identification Code|aka=Printer steganography}}\n*{{annotated link|Traitor tracing}}\n*{{annotated link|Watermark}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cs.utsa.edu/~wagner/CS1023/readings/finger.html Fingerprinting] gives a good overview of different kinds of canary trap techniques.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051024010726/http://www.eff.org/Privacy/printers/docucolor/ EFF.org DocuColor Tracking Dot Decoding Guide]  How to read the date, time, and printer serial number from forensic tracking codes in a Xerox DocuColor color laser printout.\n\n[[Category:Espionage techniques]]\n[[Category:Steganography]]\n[[Category:Computer security procedures]]\n[[Category:Watermarking]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Method for exposing an information leak by giving different versions of a sensitive document to each of several suspects}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}\nA '''canary trap''' is a method for exposing an information leak by giving different versions of a sensitive document to each of several suspects and seeing which version gets leaked. It could be one false statement, to see whether sensitive information gets out to other people as well. Special attention is paid to the quality of the prose of the unique language, in the hopes that the suspect will repeat it verbatim in the leak, thereby identifying the version of the document.\n\nThe term was coined by [[Tom Clancy]] in his novel ''[[Patriot Games]]'',<ref>{{Cite book|title=Patriot games|last=Clancy, Tom, 1947-2013.|isbn=9780440001034|oclc=1044632177}}</ref> although Clancy did not invent the technique. The actual method (usually referred to as a '''barium meal test''' in espionage circles) has been used by intelligence agencies for many years. The fictional character [[Jack Ryan (fictional character)|Jack Ryan]] describes the technique he devised for identifying the sources of leaked classified documents:\n\n<blockquote>\n''Each summary paragraph has six different versions, and the mixture of those paragraphs is unique to each numbered copy of the paper. There are over a thousand possible permutations, but only ninety-six numbered copies of the actual document. The reason the summary paragraphs are so lurid is to entice a reporter to quote them verbatim in the public media. If he quotes something from two or three of those paragraphs, we know which copy he saw and, therefore, who leaked it.'' </blockquote>\n\nA refinement of this technique uses a thesaurus program to shuffle through synonyms, thus making every copy of the document unique.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/nba-canary-trap-media-2014-12|title=The NBA Used An Espionage Trick Known As 'Canary Trap' To Catch Teams Leaking Info To The Media|last=Gaines|first=Cork|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\n==Known canary trap cases==\n\nFollowing the troubled production of ''[[Star Trek: The Motion Picture]]'' in the late 1970s, [[Paramount Pictures]] effectively replaced [[Gene Roddenberry]] as producer of [[Star Trek (film series)|further movies]] in the [[Media franchise|franchise]] with [[Harve Bennett]]. Roddenberry was retained as an \"executive consultant\", due to the high regard the series' fans held him in; while he had little real authority he was still kept involved in the creative process. The fans often complained about particular plot developments proposed for the films, such as the death of [[Spock]] in ''[[Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan|Star Trek II]]'', that Roddenberry had opposed. So, before any drafts of the screenplay for ''[[Star Trek III: The Search for Spock]]'' were circulated, Bennett arranged for each individual copy to have subtle clues distinguishing it from the others. Shortly after Roddenberry opposed the destruction of the ''[[USS Enterprise (NCC-1701)|Enterprise]]'' at the climax of that film, fans began to complain to Paramount and Bennett. He found that a leaked copy of the script was the one given to Roddenberry, but was unable to do anything about it.<ref name=\"Star Trek films\">{{cite book|last1=Engel|first1=Joel|authorlink1=|title=Gene Roddenberry: The Myth and the Man Behind ''Star Trek''|pages=[https://archive.org/details/generoddenberrym00enge/page/210 210\u201311]|date=1994|publisher=[[Hachette Books|Hyperion Books]]|isbn=0786860049|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/generoddenberrym00enge/page/210}}</ref>\n\nAfter a series of leaks at [[Tesla Motors]] in 2008, CEO [[Elon Musk]] reportedly sent slightly different versions of an e-mail to each employee in an attempt to reveal potential leakers. The e-mail was disguised as a request to employees to sign a new [[non-disclosure agreement]]. The plan was undermined when the company's general counsel forwarded his own unique version of the e-mail with the attached agreement. As a result, Musk's scheme was realized by employees who now had a safe copy to leak.<ref>{{cite web \n |url=http://gawker.com/5164035/tesla-ceo-in-digital-witch-hunt \n |author=Owen Thomas \n |year=2009 \n |title=Tesla CEO in Digital Witch Hunt \n |accessdate=2013-11-16 \n |publisher=[[Gawker Media]] \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020092330/http://gawker.com/5164035/tesla-ceo-in-digital-witch-hunt \n |archivedate=2013-10-20 \n }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, it was proposed as a method for the [[Presidency of Donald Trump| Trump Administration]] to catch leaks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/whats-in-sessions-toolkit-for-hunting-anti-trump-leakers|title=What's in Sessions' toolkit for hunting anti-Trump leakers?|last=Wallace|first=Christopher|date=2017-08-04|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, British celebrity [[Coleen Rooney]] used the technique to identify who was leaking information from her private [[Instagram]] stories to tabloid newspaper [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] by posting fake stories which were blocked to all but one account. When these details appeared in the press, she publicly identified the leaks as coming from the account of Rebekah Vardy, wife of footballer [[Jamie Vardy]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosseinsky |first1=Katie |year=2019 |title=Coleen Rooney accuses Rebekah Vardy's Instagram account of leaking stories to the press |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/colleen-rooney-accuses-rebekah-vardy-of-leaking-stories-about-her-a4257461.html |website=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=2019-10-09}}</ref>.\n\n==Barium meal test==\nAccording to the book ''[[Spycatcher]]''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Spycatcher|last=Wright, Peter, 1916-1995.|date=1989|publisher=Mandarin|isbn=1863300007|oclc=27626618}}</ref> by [[Peter Wright (MI5 officer)|Peter Wright]] (published in 1987) the technique is standard practice that has been used by [[MI5]] (and other intelligence agencies) for many years, under the name \"[[barium meal]] test\". A barium meal test is more sophisticated than a canary trap because it is flexible and may take many different forms. However, the basic premise is to reveal a secret to a suspected enemy (but nobody else) then monitor whether there is evidence of the fake information being utilised by the other side. For example, a suspected double agent could be offered some tempting \"bait\": e.g., be told that important information was stored at a [[dead drop]] site. The fake dead drop site could then be periodically checked for signs of disturbance. If the site showed signs of being disturbed (for instance, in order to copy microfilm stored there), then this would confirm that the suspected enemy really was an enemy, i.e., a double agent.\n\n==Embedding information==\nThe technique of embedding significant information in a hidden form in a medium has been used in many ways, which are usually classified according to intent:\n\n* [[Watermark]]s are used to show that items are authentic and not forged.\n* [[Steganography]] is used to hide a secret message in an apparently innocuous message, in order to escape detection.\n* A canary trap hides information in a document that uniquely identifies it, so that copies of it can be traced.\n* [[Screener (promotional)|Screener]] versions of DVDs are often marked in some way so as to allow the tracking of unauthorised releases to their source.\n* As with the ''Star Trek'' incident, major films or television productions frequently give out scripts to the cast and crew in which one or two lines are different in each individual version. Thus if the entire script is copied and leaked to the public, the producers can track down the specific person who leaked the script. In practice this does not prevent generalized information about the script from being leaked, but it does discourage leaking verbatim copies of the script itself.\n* [[Trap street]]s on maps, or intentionally fictitious streets, are sometimes included to track copyright violations by those who might republish copyrighted maps illegally.\n* [[Fictitious entry|Spurious words]] are sometimes included in dictionaries so as to detect other publishers copying from them. The [[OED]] contains an appendix of such words with which edition of which dictionary first used them and which first duplicated them.\n* [[Zero-width spaces]] are Unicode characters that are not visually rendered. An arbitrary number of these characters can be inserted betw&#8203;een the letters of a word. Though they are not visible, they will typically persist even as that word is copied and pasted and transmitted multiple times. This can be used to create persistent, invisible fingerprints in digital text.<ref>{{cite website|url=https://www.zachaysan.com/writing/2017-12-30-zero-width-characters|title=Zero-Width Characters - Invisibly fingerprinting text|author=Zach Aysan}}</ref>\n* [[Mailing lists]] for purchase are typically seeded with a small number of postal or e-mail addresses that route back to the seller of the list. This is used to detect re-use of the list (typically sold on a per-mailing basis) or resale of the list (usually prohibited).\n\n==In popular culture==\n\n* The canary trap was used in several of Tom Clancy's novels.  Chronologically it first appears in ''[[Without Remorse]]'', when a CIA official alters a report given to a senator, revealing an internal leak who was giving information to the [[KGB]].  Different versions of the report were given to other suspected leaks.\n* Barium meals are also administered in Robert Littel's book ''[[The Company (Littell novel)|The Company]]'', and later in the TV miniseries with same name.\n* The technique (not named) was used in the 1970s BBC television serial ''[[1990 (TV series)|1990]]''.  The same unnamed technique also appeared in [[Irving Wallace]]'s book ''[[The Word (novel)|The Word]]'' (1972).\n* A variation of the canary trap was used in the film ''[[Miami Vice (film)|Miami Vice]]'', with various rendezvous dates leaked to different groups.\n* In the [[Strawberries and Cream (The Mentalist)|third-season finale]] of ''[[The Mentalist]]'', the characters use a canary trap (giving different hotel room numbers to different suspects) to uncover a [[Mole (espionage)|mole]] within their agency. A similar ruse is used in the TV series ''[[Ashes to Ashes (TV series)|Ashes to Ashes]]''.\n* In ''[[A Clash of Kings]]'', the second book in the [[A Song of Ice and Fire]] series, [[Tyrion Lannister]] uses the trap to find out which member of the King's [[Privy Council]] is reporting to his sister, the Queen Regent [[Cersei Lannister]]. To the Grand Maester Pycelle, he tells of a plot to marry his niece, [[Myrcella Baratheon|Princess Myrcella]], to Prince [[Trystane Martell|Trystane]] of the powerful [[House Martell]], from [[Dorne]]. To [[Petyr Baelish|Littlefinger]], he claims he will instead send Myrcella to be raised by [[Lysa Arryn]] and married to her son Robert. To [[Varys]], he says his plan is to send his nephew [[Tommen Baratheon|Tommen]] to the Martells. When Cersei confronts him, and knows only of the plan to send Myrcella to Dorne, Tyrion knows Pycelle to be the leak.\n** This plotline is also depicted in \"[[What Is Dead May Never Die]]\", during [[Game of Thrones (season 2)|the second season]] of ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', the television adaptation of the books.\n* When distributing the film ''[[Broken (1993 film)|Broken]]'' to friends, [[Trent Reznor]] claims that he watermarked the tapes with dropouts at certain points so that he could identify if a leak would surface.\n* In the film ''[[The Heat (film)|The Heat]]'' starring Melissa McCarthy and Sandra Bullock, a canary trap is employed by a drug ring to decide the loyalty of a returning member who is detective Mullins' brother.\n* In ''Han Solo at Stars' End'', the first book in ''[[The Han Solo Adventures]]'', the title character uses a canary trap to find a traitor and murderer among his passengers.  He tells each that their target is a different planet, all false, knowing that the traitor would have learned the real destination when they killed the group's leader.\n\n==See also==\n*{{annotated link|Recruitment of spies|aka=Clandestine HUMINT asset recruiting}}\n*{{annotated link|Coded anti-piracy}}\n*{{annotated link|Fictitious entry}}\n*{{annotated link|Honeytoken}}\n*{{annotated link|Machine Identification Code|aka=Printer steganography}}\n*{{annotated link|Traitor tracing}}\n*{{annotated link|Watermark}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cs.utsa.edu/~wagner/CS1023/readings/finger.html Fingerprinting] gives a good overview of different kinds of canary trap techniques.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051024010726/http://www.eff.org/Privacy/printers/docucolor/ EFF.org DocuColor Tracking Dot Decoding Guide]  How to read the date, time, and printer serial number from forensic tracking codes in a Xerox DocuColor color laser printout.\n\n[[Category:Espionage techniques]]\n[[Category:Steganography]]\n[[Category:Computer security procedures]]\n[[Category:Watermarking]]\n", "name_user": "Eric", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIn popular culture:rv odd error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canary_trap"}
